1
00:00:05,204 --> 00:00:08,172
[Michael] Stanford University,
 1973.

2
00:00:08,173 --> 00:00:09,674
 Professor Philip Zimbardo
 conducts

3
00:00:09,675 --> 00:00:11,443
 one of the most infamous
 experiments

4
00:00:11,444 --> 00:00:13,678
 in the history
 of psychology.

5
00:00:13,679 --> 00:00:16,281
 Known as the Stanford
 Prison Experiment,

6
00:00:16,282 --> 00:00:19,484
 this dark study
 of human behavior
 had student volunteers

7
00:00:19,485 --> 00:00:22,720
 acting out the roles of
 prison guards and inmates.

8
00:00:22,721 --> 00:00:25,390
 But the role-playing soon
 became all too real.

9
00:00:25,391 --> 00:00:28,359
[man shouting]

10
00:00:28,360 --> 00:00:30,128
 Subjects in the role
 of prison guards

11
00:00:30,129 --> 00:00:32,097
 became domineering
 and hostile.

12
00:00:32,098 --> 00:00:37,435
[participants shouting]

13
00:00:37,436 --> 00:00:45,677
 Those in the role of inmates
 felt humiliation and fear.

14
00:00:45,678 --> 00:00:48,446
 The experiment was scheduled
 to last two weeks,

15
00:00:48,447 --> 00:00:50,682
 but after spiraling
 out of control,

16
00:00:50,683 --> 00:00:52,250
 this controversial study

17
00:00:52,251 --> 00:00:55,854
 was abruptly stopped
 after just six days.

18
00:00:55,855 --> 00:00:58,656
Why? Because someone
was heroic enough

19
00:00:58,657 --> 00:01:01,826
to stand up against
what they thought was wrong.

20
00:01:01,827 --> 00:01:05,396
That person convinced
Zimbardo to end the experiment.

21
00:01:05,397 --> 00:01:08,833
The experience affected
Dr. Zimbardo so powerfully

22
00:01:08,834 --> 00:01:10,735
that he has since
turned his energy

23
00:01:10,736 --> 00:01:12,437
away from the study of evil

24
00:01:12,438 --> 00:01:14,806
and onto the study
of heroism.

25
00:01:14,807 --> 00:01:17,342
According to Zimbardo,
being a hero doesn't mean

26
00:01:17,343 --> 00:01:19,544
you have to rescue someone
from a burning building.

27
00:01:19,545 --> 00:01:23,248
A hero is just someone
who acts selflessly,

28
00:01:23,249 --> 00:01:24,849
out of concern for others,

29
00:01:24,850 --> 00:01:26,618
at personal risk

30
00:01:26,619 --> 00:01:29,821
and without the expectation
of reward.

31
00:01:29,822 --> 00:01:32,190
It took a hero to empathize
with the subjects

32
00:01:32,191 --> 00:01:34,192
in the Stanford
Prison Experiment

33
00:01:34,193 --> 00:01:36,561
 and stand up to Dr. Zimbardo.

34
00:01:36,562 --> 00:01:38,730
 But where do heroes
 like that come from?

35
00:01:38,731 --> 00:01:41,499
Is heroism a personality type
you are born with,

36
00:01:41,500 --> 00:01:44,536
or can you be taught
to be a hero?

37
00:01:44,537 --> 00:01:47,605
And do you really need a cape?

38
00:01:47,606 --> 00:02:06,524
[theme music playing]

39
00:02:06,525 --> 00:02:08,726
[Michael] I sat down
 with Philip Zimbardo

40
00:02:08,727 --> 00:02:10,962
 and his wife,
 Christine Maslach,

41
00:02:10,963 --> 00:02:12,797
 to hear about
the Stanford Prison Experiment

42
00:02:12,798 --> 00:02:14,699
 and how it brought them
 together as a couple.

43
00:02:14,700 --> 00:02:16,367
The Stanford prison study

44
00:02:16,368 --> 00:02:17,802
was supposed to go
for two weeks,

45
00:02:17,803 --> 00:02:20,405
and we had to
terminate it early

46
00:02:20,406 --> 00:02:24,876
because of some unexpected
turbulence in the study.

47
00:02:24,877 --> 00:02:28,213
I was just really upset
at what I was seeing,

48
00:02:28,214 --> 00:02:29,814
and, um,

49
00:02:29,815 --> 00:02:31,549
just the sort of dehumanization

50
00:02:31,550 --> 00:02:32,884
and-and people are watching,

51
00:02:32,885 --> 00:02:34,919
and nobody's bothered by it.

52
00:02:34,920 --> 00:02:37,288
And it wasn't just Phil,
it was everybody else.

53
00:02:37,289 --> 00:02:39,224
People were sort of
teasing me,

54
00:02:39,225 --> 00:02:40,892
some of the other grad students
were just saying,

55
00:02:40,893 --> 00:02:42,894
"Hey, you just got your PhD
in Psychology.

56
00:02:42,895 --> 00:02:44,762
This is human behavior,
right?"

57
00:02:44,763 --> 00:02:46,598
But it's upsetting
in two ways:

58
00:02:46,599 --> 00:02:48,900
one, that this shouldn't
be human behavior.

59
00:02:48,901 --> 00:02:51,336
This is so mean.
But also--

60
00:02:51,337 --> 00:02:52,837
-It's inhuman behavior.
-It's inhuman behavior.

61
00:02:52,838 --> 00:02:54,739
And also,
is it also inhuman

62
00:02:54,740 --> 00:02:56,674
to just watch it
and not intervene?

63
00:02:56,675 --> 00:02:58,910
Of course.
In retrospect.

64
00:02:58,911 --> 00:03:02,547
No, but when you're in it,
you're part of the evil.

65
00:03:02,548 --> 00:03:03,815
I was looking at it
through a different lens.

66
00:03:03,816 --> 00:03:05,416
Everybody is saying,
the graduates,

67
00:03:05,417 --> 00:03:07,318
"Wow, this is really
interesting."

68
00:03:07,319 --> 00:03:09,587
...playing back the videos
during the night,

69
00:03:09,588 --> 00:03:11,456
and she's just saying...
[sharp whistle]

70
00:03:11,457 --> 00:03:13,558
"I'm blowing the whistle
on this, you know?"

71
00:03:13,559 --> 00:03:15,493
I could not understand

72
00:03:15,494 --> 00:03:19,464
how we were not seeing things
in the same way.

73
00:03:19,465 --> 00:03:20,431
But then the key thing
she says

74
00:03:20,432 --> 00:03:23,568
about our relationship is...

75
00:03:23,569 --> 00:03:26,037
[chuckles] Yeah.
"If this is the real you,
then we're done.

76
00:03:26,038 --> 00:03:28,273
This is over."

77
00:03:28,274 --> 00:03:29,974
And at that moment,
that was the slap in the fa--

78
00:03:29,975 --> 00:03:32,477
That was the wakeup call.
"Hello. Wake up."

79
00:03:32,478 --> 00:03:34,345
She said, "I don't think
I want to continue

80
00:03:34,346 --> 00:03:37,615
my relationship with you,"
and that's-that's heroic.

81
00:03:37,616 --> 00:03:39,050
Heroes take action,

82
00:03:39,051 --> 00:03:41,519
which involves a personal risk.

83
00:03:41,520 --> 00:03:43,888
She said,
"Come to your senses,"

84
00:03:43,889 --> 00:03:45,957
and, parentheses,
"Make the right decision.

85
00:03:45,958 --> 00:03:48,559
And if you don't,
I'm out of here."

86
00:03:48,560 --> 00:03:50,962
Did you make the decision
to end the experiment
that night?

87
00:03:50,963 --> 00:03:59,637
-Oh, sure.
-Yeah.

88
00:03:59,638 --> 00:04:00,738
 Being a hero

89
00:04:00,739 --> 00:04:03,541
means putting yourself
on the line to help others.

90
00:04:03,542 --> 00:04:06,511
But in the real world,
ethics can get murky,

91
00:04:06,512 --> 00:04:09,080
and those who are celebrated
as heroes by some

92
00:04:09,081 --> 00:04:12,050
can be denounced as villains
by others.

93
00:04:12,051 --> 00:04:16,054
In 1971, former military
analyst Daniel Ellsberg

94
00:04:16,055 --> 00:04:18,456
 leaked secret documents
 he had access to

95
00:04:18,457 --> 00:04:19,857
 regarding the Vietnam War.

96
00:04:19,858 --> 00:04:21,958
 The so-called Pentagon Papers

97
00:04:21,959 --> 00:04:23,795
showed that
the Johnson administration

98
00:04:23,796 --> 00:04:26,331
was lying to both the media
and Congress

99
00:04:26,332 --> 00:04:28,766
regarding the scope of
U.S. actions in Vietnam.

100
00:04:28,767 --> 00:04:32,437
 Ellsberg faced 115 years
 in prison for espionage,

101
00:04:32,438 --> 00:04:34,605
 But his case was dismissed
 due to illegal handling

102
00:04:34,606 --> 00:04:36,374
 of evidence on the part
 of the government.

103
00:04:36,375 --> 00:04:39,043
 More recently,
 both Chelsea Manning

104
00:04:39,044 --> 00:04:42,113
 and Edward Snowden
 released classified
 government information.

105
00:04:42,114 --> 00:04:43,881
 All three whistle-blowers

106
00:04:43,882 --> 00:04:45,917
 are now seen as heroes
 by some

107
00:04:45,918 --> 00:04:48,419
and traitors by others.

108
00:04:48,420 --> 00:04:50,421
What these individuals
have in common

109
00:04:50,422 --> 00:04:53,891
is that they all risked
their reputations and safety

110
00:04:53,892 --> 00:04:57,061
to expose what they saw
as wrongdoing.

111
00:04:57,062 --> 00:04:59,063
Would you be willing
to risk your job,

112
00:04:59,064 --> 00:05:01,566
your friends,
your reputation,

113
00:05:01,567 --> 00:05:03,735
to do what you
thought was right?

114
00:05:03,736 --> 00:05:05,870
Well, to find out,
let's observe

115
00:05:05,871 --> 00:05:07,772
the whistleblower
and the bystander

116
00:05:07,773 --> 00:05:14,846
in their natural habitat.

117
00:05:14,847 --> 00:05:17,081
 In a 2012 survey
 conducted by Dr. Zimbardo

118
00:05:17,082 --> 00:05:18,516
 and Dr. Piero Bocchiaro,

119
00:05:18,517 --> 00:05:20,685
 participants were asked
 what they would do

120
00:05:20,686 --> 00:05:23,588
 if they were put into
an unethical situation at work.

121
00:05:23,589 --> 00:05:24,989
 Over 95% said they would
 disobey their boss

122
00:05:24,990 --> 00:05:27,625
 and blow the whistle.

123
00:05:27,626 --> 00:05:29,861
 But it's one thing to say
 you'd blow the whistle,

124
00:05:29,862 --> 00:05:32,397
 and another thing
 to actually do it.

125
00:05:32,398 --> 00:05:34,399
 At a local community college,

126
00:05:34,400 --> 00:05:36,567
 we set up a realistic
 whistleblower test

127
00:05:36,568 --> 00:05:37,635
 with the help
 of Dr. Zimbardo

128
00:05:37,636 --> 00:05:39,804
 and Dr. Bocchiaro.

129
00:05:39,805 --> 00:05:42,073
 Our subjects
 were temporary employees

130
00:05:42,074 --> 00:05:44,075
 who believed they were hired
 to help set up

131
00:05:44,076 --> 00:05:48,112
 a simple psychological
 experiment.

132
00:05:48,113 --> 00:05:49,480
 For authenticity,

133
00:05:49,481 --> 00:05:51,883
we've gained access
to a local college's
Psychology department,

134
00:05:51,884 --> 00:05:54,852
so, from the very moment
our participants arrive,

135
00:05:54,853 --> 00:05:58,956
they will believe that our
scientific experiment is real.

136
00:05:58,957 --> 00:06:01,592
 But the experiment is fake,

137
00:06:01,593 --> 00:06:03,961
 and everyone they're
 about to meet is an actor.

138
00:06:03,962 --> 00:06:05,062
You guys ready?

139
00:06:05,063 --> 00:06:06,697
-Absolutely.
-So ready.

140
00:06:06,698 --> 00:06:08,099
 Psychology professor
 Ron Mossler

141
00:06:08,100 --> 00:06:09,634
 will be observing
 the subjects

142
00:06:09,635 --> 00:06:11,569
 from our hidden control room,

143
00:06:11,570 --> 00:06:13,771
 while I play the role
 of a researcher,

144
00:06:13,772 --> 00:06:16,007
 a very unethical researcher.

145
00:06:16,008 --> 00:06:17,041
 First up is Sherry...

146
00:06:17,042 --> 00:06:18,943
-Hello.
-Hello.

147
00:06:18,944 --> 00:06:20,711
 ...who's accompanied
 by an actor

148
00:06:20,712 --> 00:06:22,613
 posing as
 another temp worker.

149
00:06:22,614 --> 00:06:25,183
Let me explain
what we're recruiting for.

150
00:06:25,184 --> 00:06:28,119
I call it groundbreaking
because it's...

151
00:06:28,120 --> 00:06:30,788
it's a study that
hasn't been done,
at least at this scale.

152
00:06:30,789 --> 00:06:32,957
The study is a study
on isolation

153
00:06:32,958 --> 00:06:34,492
and sensory deprivation.

154
00:06:34,493 --> 00:06:36,227
-Sensory deprivation?
-Correct.

155
00:06:36,228 --> 00:06:38,196
We are going to be putting
people in isolation

156
00:06:38,197 --> 00:06:40,665
for ten days.

157
00:06:40,666 --> 00:06:42,800
There won't be any windows,
no clocks,

158
00:06:42,801 --> 00:06:44,902
nothing to read,
nothing to write on.

159
00:06:44,903 --> 00:06:47,505
The lights are going to be on
the entire time,

160
00:06:47,506 --> 00:06:49,073
and there won't be anything
in there

161
00:06:49,074 --> 00:06:52,009
but a camping toilet.

162
00:06:52,010 --> 00:06:52,977
In three-day studies,

163
00:06:52,978 --> 00:06:55,546
we know that anxiety

164
00:06:55,547 --> 00:06:57,982
and delusions
are quite common,

165
00:06:57,983 --> 00:07:00,117
but no one's
ever tried ten days.

166
00:07:00,118 --> 00:07:03,020
There's the potential
for nervous breakdowns.

167
00:07:03,021 --> 00:07:05,089
There's a lot of stress
on the individual,

168
00:07:05,090 --> 00:07:08,593
and, uh, there can be
some kind of cognitive
regression, as well.

169
00:07:08,594 --> 00:07:12,129
When will you tell them
about the risks?

170
00:07:12,130 --> 00:07:13,831
They'll probably be told
about the risks

171
00:07:13,832 --> 00:07:15,199
in a debrief
after the experiment.

172
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:18,202
 -After the experiment?
-Yes.

173
00:07:18,203 --> 00:07:20,671
Don't you think that's
a little not so cool.

174
00:07:20,672 --> 00:07:22,006
I-I understand.

175
00:07:22,007 --> 00:07:24,008
But, again, I think
that the greater good

176
00:07:24,009 --> 00:07:25,643
is served by this research.

177
00:07:25,644 --> 00:07:27,044
So, you'll just be
manning phones,

178
00:07:27,045 --> 00:07:29,146
calling people
from our volunteer lists,

179
00:07:29,147 --> 00:07:31,616
and for every person
you're able to confirm today,

180
00:07:31,617 --> 00:07:33,284
we're offering a $20 bonus.

181
00:07:33,285 --> 00:07:35,920
 At this point,
 Sherry looks skeptical.

182
00:07:35,921 --> 00:07:37,822
 but so far,
 she and our other subjects

183
00:07:37,823 --> 00:07:39,891
 are going along
 with the assignment.

184
00:07:39,892 --> 00:07:43,628
 However, the stakes
 are about to get higher.

185
00:07:43,629 --> 00:07:44,962
We have lists of people--

186
00:07:44,963 --> 00:07:47,098
[telephone rings]

187
00:07:47,099 --> 00:07:48,766
Don't know why that's--

188
00:07:48,767 --> 00:07:50,535
Hello?

189
00:07:50,536 --> 00:07:51,869
Hi, Michael,
this is Tryn.

190
00:07:51,870 --> 00:07:52,770
Hey, Tryn, how you doing?

191
00:07:52,771 --> 00:07:56,607
Well, unfortunately,
I have some bad news.

192
00:07:56,608 --> 00:08:00,845
The ethics review board
has reviewed
your isolation study,

193
00:08:00,846 --> 00:08:05,583
and we have decided
to reject it.

194
00:08:05,584 --> 00:08:06,618
You there, Tryn?

195
00:08:06,619 --> 00:08:08,586
[Tryn] Yes, the study
 is too dangerous,

196
00:08:08,587 --> 00:08:09,954
 um, and potentially

197
00:08:09,955 --> 00:08:12,657
too harmful to participants,
so, at this point,

198
00:08:12,658 --> 00:08:14,292
 we can't approve it.

199
00:08:14,293 --> 00:08:17,929
Okay, uh, so this is
a shutdown.

200
00:08:17,930 --> 00:08:18,864
 Correct.

201
00:08:18,865 --> 00:08:23,100
 -All right, take care. Bye.
-Bye-bye.

202
00:08:23,101 --> 00:08:24,168
Uh, okay.

203
00:08:24,169 --> 00:08:26,003
So, we're not paying
attention to any of that.

204
00:08:26,004 --> 00:08:28,139
[laughter]

205
00:08:28,140 --> 00:08:30,775
I-I appreciate
what ethic boards stand for,

206
00:08:30,776 --> 00:08:32,643
but we're going ten days.

207
00:08:32,644 --> 00:08:36,614
You call the numbers
on this list and get
them confirmed.

208
00:08:36,615 --> 00:08:38,749
We've got a script for you,
and we're not going to tell them

209
00:08:38,750 --> 00:08:42,186
about the negative side effects
they could encounter, okay?

210
00:08:42,187 --> 00:08:44,221
 All of the subjects
 now understood

211
00:08:44,222 --> 00:08:47,091
 the possible dangerous
 side effects of the study

212
00:08:47,092 --> 00:08:49,327
 and were instructed
 to fudge their description

213
00:08:49,328 --> 00:08:50,661
 to potential recruits.

214
00:08:50,662 --> 00:08:52,830
 But more importantly,

215
00:08:52,831 --> 00:08:54,165
 they knew the study
 was not approved

216
00:08:54,166 --> 00:08:56,367
 by the academic review board.

217
00:08:56,368 --> 00:08:58,102
 Would they go ahead
 and tell the truth,

218
00:08:58,103 --> 00:09:00,304
 lie, or blow the whistle?

219
00:09:00,305 --> 00:09:02,807
[cell phone rings]

220
00:09:02,808 --> 00:09:04,308
Hello.

221
00:09:04,309 --> 00:09:06,711
Hi, Alex, my name is Celeste,

222
00:09:06,712 --> 00:09:09,046
and I am calling from
the Psych Dynamics Research Lab.

223
00:09:09,047 --> 00:09:11,616
We're looking for volunteers
to participate

224
00:09:11,617 --> 00:09:13,851
in an upcoming experiment
on isolation.

225
00:09:13,852 --> 00:09:15,920
Anyone who joins this
will be confined

226
00:09:15,921 --> 00:09:17,655
in isolation for ten days.

227
00:09:17,656 --> 00:09:19,824
What's
the accommodations like?

228
00:09:19,825 --> 00:09:21,359
You get your own personal room,

229
00:09:21,360 --> 00:09:23,361
it's all lit up...

230
00:09:23,362 --> 00:09:26,230
-She's really selling this.
-Yeah.

231
00:09:26,231 --> 00:09:31,102
She was not fazed
by the ethical problems.

232
00:09:31,103 --> 00:09:33,871
Can I bring, like, a book
or something like that?

233
00:09:33,872 --> 00:09:36,007
Nnn...no, it's like
your own little mini vacation

234
00:09:36,008 --> 00:09:37,642
from all the distractions.

235
00:09:37,643 --> 00:09:39,844
I mean, like,
what are the risks

236
00:09:39,845 --> 00:09:41,245
of being in a box
without a bed for ten days?

237
00:09:41,246 --> 00:09:42,980
Good question.

238
00:09:42,981 --> 00:09:44,382
I mean, that's what
the study's for.

239
00:09:44,383 --> 00:09:47,385
You'd be helping us
discover that.

240
00:09:47,386 --> 00:09:49,320
Have they done it before?

241
00:09:49,321 --> 00:09:51,822
They haven't done it yet
in California.

242
00:09:51,823 --> 00:09:54,892
So, we're actually
making history.

243
00:09:54,893 --> 00:09:56,293
Oh, well, all right,
I like making history.

244
00:09:56,294 --> 00:09:58,729
Are there any, like,
mental health risks?

245
00:09:58,730 --> 00:10:01,098
No.

246
00:10:01,099 --> 00:10:02,767
There's no risks
or anything like that?

247
00:10:02,768 --> 00:10:04,835
No. No, flashing lights,

248
00:10:04,836 --> 00:10:07,038
no fear dynamic,

249
00:10:07,039 --> 00:10:08,239
not a horror movie
in any way now.

250
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:09,774
He knows there are dangers.

251
00:10:09,775 --> 00:10:11,409
They're on a piece of paper
right in front of him.

252
00:10:11,410 --> 00:10:13,678
But when asked
if there are dangers,

253
00:10:13,679 --> 00:10:15,446
he labels other dangers
that won't be there.

254
00:10:15,447 --> 00:10:17,181
There's no endangerment.

255
00:10:17,182 --> 00:10:19,250
There'll be no one
in the room with you.

