that's gonna be
on the market.

509
00:20:01,866 --> 00:20:04,601
-Wow! How exciting!
-Yeah.

510
00:20:04,602 --> 00:20:07,504
So, it's just gonna be,
like, another ten or 15
minutes.

511
00:20:07,505 --> 00:20:09,306
But before I can let
you guys back though,

512
00:20:09,307 --> 00:20:11,608
I will need to collect
your phones.

513
00:20:11,609 --> 00:20:14,011
We took their phones so they
wouldn't be distracted

514
00:20:14,012 --> 00:20:15,846
and to avoid the chance of one
of them

515
00:20:15,847 --> 00:20:17,848
calling the actual police.

516
00:20:17,849 --> 00:20:19,783
Okay, Lisa, Barry,
you guys ready?

517
00:20:19,784 --> 00:20:21,685
-Yeah.
-Head on out.

518
00:20:21,686 --> 00:20:23,987
 It was time to create
 our crisis...

519
00:20:23,988 --> 00:20:25,656
I was supposed to get cake.

520
00:20:25,657 --> 00:20:27,924
Barry, enough
with the cake.

521
00:20:27,925 --> 00:20:30,861
 ...a bullying nurse
 and a feeble old man

522
00:20:30,862 --> 00:20:34,031
 who could use some help
 from a hero on a hot day in
 July.

523
00:20:34,032 --> 00:20:35,632
I didn't have water
in there.

524
00:20:35,633 --> 00:20:38,568
I need you
to shut up about the water.

525
00:20:38,569 --> 00:20:40,470
I think she's noticing
what's happening.

526
00:20:40,471 --> 00:20:41,972
[Lisa] Hey, Sally,
how you doing?

527
00:20:41,973 --> 00:20:43,807
-Always, always--
-I need water.

528
00:20:43,808 --> 00:20:46,476
Calm down!
I'm on the phone. Shut up.

529
00:20:46,477 --> 00:20:47,678
Can I just take
some water?

530
00:20:47,679 --> 00:20:49,379
Well, you know how Barry is.

531
00:20:49,380 --> 00:20:50,580
He's always complaining
about something.

532
00:20:50,581 --> 00:20:52,316
 Now she's looking away.

533
00:20:52,317 --> 00:20:53,917
It's a little hard
to look at.

534
00:20:53,918 --> 00:20:55,085
Like, that's not right.
I don't like this.

535
00:20:55,086 --> 00:20:56,820
I need
a little bit of water.

536
00:20:56,821 --> 00:20:58,088
I don't think
you need anything.

537
00:20:58,089 --> 00:21:00,357
Just shut up
about the water.

538
00:21:00,358 --> 00:21:02,626
[Elle] Look how she just
puts her sunglasses on.

539
00:21:02,627 --> 00:21:05,762
So she can look
and not be seen
to be looking.

540
00:21:05,763 --> 00:21:07,731
 Ayamel clearly disapproved,

541
00:21:07,732 --> 00:21:09,866
 but none of our actors
 made a move to help,

542
00:21:09,867 --> 00:21:11,735
 and she didn't either.

543
00:21:11,736 --> 00:21:13,337
 We gave her
 several more minutes,

544
00:21:13,338 --> 00:21:14,805
 but she never got up
 from the bench.

545
00:21:14,806 --> 00:21:16,907
-Let's go.
 -We wanted to know why.

546
00:21:16,908 --> 00:21:20,811
So, you've just participated
in a psychological experiment.

547
00:21:20,812 --> 00:21:23,780
Everyone here is an actor,
except for you.

548
00:21:23,781 --> 00:21:25,982
-[laughing]
-And something has gone wrong.

549
00:21:25,983 --> 00:21:28,018
[indistinct remark]

550
00:21:28,019 --> 00:21:31,421
Were you watching
Barry and Lisa?

551
00:21:31,422 --> 00:21:34,691
Oh, I was... and they were
having a hard time.

552
00:21:34,692 --> 00:21:36,793
Did you feel like
it was bad enough

553
00:21:36,794 --> 00:21:39,629
that someone needed
to go in and help?

554
00:21:39,630 --> 00:21:41,932
I kind of trusted
that the people around me

555
00:21:41,933 --> 00:21:43,734
would probably notice something,
and, if anything,

556
00:21:43,735 --> 00:21:45,402
they would say something.

557
00:21:45,403 --> 00:21:47,804
The way that you
interpreted the situation

558
00:21:47,805 --> 00:21:51,041
as, you know, "Why isn't
anyone else doing something?

559
00:21:51,042 --> 00:21:53,110
Then it must not be
as important for me
to do something."

560
00:21:53,111 --> 00:21:54,911
That's
the bystander effect,

561
00:21:54,912 --> 00:21:58,548
pretty much showing
the power of that situation.

562
00:21:58,549 --> 00:22:00,784
 Ayamel did not
 act heroically.

563
00:22:00,785 --> 00:22:02,419
 It was time to test
 a HIP student.

564
00:22:02,420 --> 00:22:04,454
 Remember Courtney?

565
00:22:04,455 --> 00:22:07,090
I would definitely be
the first person to respond

566
00:22:07,091 --> 00:22:08,692
because that person
needs saving.

567
00:22:08,693 --> 00:22:10,127
[happy chatter]

568
00:22:10,128 --> 00:22:12,529
[man]
What is your tattoo?

569
00:22:12,530 --> 00:22:14,664
Oh, it's fallopian tubes
giving the middle finger.

570
00:22:14,665 --> 00:22:17,167
-[man] Oh, wow.
-[laughter]

571
00:22:17,168 --> 00:22:19,569
-Seems like she's pretty
socially active.
-Yes.

572
00:22:19,570 --> 00:22:21,671
Lisa, please,
a little bit of water.

573
00:22:21,672 --> 00:22:23,874
[Lisa] If you stop talking,
you won't be as thirsty.

574
00:22:23,875 --> 00:22:25,675
Why won't you
give me water?

575
00:22:25,676 --> 00:22:28,078
How many times do I have
to explain this to you?

576
00:22:28,079 --> 00:22:38,188
Every time you drink water,
you have to go to the restroom.

577
00:22:38,189 --> 00:22:41,091
[Lisa] Hey,
how's it going?

578
00:22:41,092 --> 00:22:44,728
He's being his regular
rambunctious self.

579
00:22:44,729 --> 00:22:46,129
I need you--
I'm on the phone!

580
00:22:46,130 --> 00:22:47,831
[gasps]

581
00:22:47,832 --> 00:22:50,000
-Wow. Awkward.
-That's hard to ignore.

582
00:22:50,001 --> 00:22:51,735
Hey, calm down.

583
00:22:51,736 --> 00:22:53,203
[Barry] I'm calm,
I'm calm.

584
00:22:53,204 --> 00:22:54,971
-Oh, she's getting up!
-Yes!

585
00:22:54,972 --> 00:22:57,174
[Lisa] Look, I'm just
gonna have to let you go.

586
00:22:57,175 --> 00:22:58,775
Yeah, for sure.

587
00:22:58,776 --> 00:23:01,511
Bye.

588
00:23:01,512 --> 00:23:03,447
I told you, whenever
I'm on the phone,

589
00:23:03,448 --> 00:23:05,849
to not talk or do
anything like this.

590
00:23:05,850 --> 00:23:09,986
You have totally lost
your water privileges
for the rest of the day.

591
00:23:09,987 --> 00:23:12,656
-Why can't I have water?
-[gasps]

592
00:23:12,657 --> 00:23:13,957
Why are you not
letting me have water?

593
00:23:13,958 --> 00:23:15,926
[Courtney] Excuse me,
is everything okay?

594
00:23:15,927 --> 00:23:16,760
[Lisa]
Yeah, everything's fine.

595
00:23:16,761 --> 00:23:18,795
Would you like some
of my water, sir?

596
00:23:18,796 --> 00:23:21,665
-I would like some water.
-[Michael] Oh, my gosh.

597
00:23:21,666 --> 00:23:23,133
[Courtney] I will make sure
I find a supervisor

598
00:23:23,134 --> 00:23:25,101
onsite for you, sir.

599
00:23:25,102 --> 00:23:25,735
I'm very sorry,
that's all I have.

600
00:23:25,736 --> 00:23:27,204
That's alright, thank you.

601
00:23:27,205 --> 00:23:29,506
 Courtney displayed
 heroism today.

602
00:23:29,507 --> 00:23:30,874
 Was it due to her
 HIP training?

603
00:23:30,875 --> 00:23:32,175
My name's Elle.

604
00:23:32,176 --> 00:23:34,578
I've been working with
Heroic Imagination Project,

605
00:23:34,579 --> 00:23:35,812
and it looks like you
may have learned

606
00:23:35,813 --> 00:23:37,714
a few things
from your lessons.

607
00:23:37,715 --> 00:23:39,649
Do you want
to tell us a little bit
about your experience?

608
00:23:39,650 --> 00:23:41,718
You shouldn't be
a bystander, you know?

609
00:23:41,719 --> 00:23:43,153
I just couldn't
let it it happen.

610
00:23:43,154 --> 00:23:44,921
How did that affect
how you acted today?

611
00:23:44,922 --> 00:23:47,591
It affected me 'cause
I made sure

612
00:23:47,592 --> 00:23:49,993
I went up and said something.
I don't think I would have

613
00:23:49,994 --> 00:23:52,128
if I didn't learn
from that project before.

614
00:23:52,129 --> 00:23:54,664
Really? Courtney,
you are a hero.

615
00:23:54,665 --> 00:23:56,233
Good work.

616
00:23:56,234 --> 00:23:57,868
-Thank you, Courtney.
-Thank you.

617
00:23:57,869 --> 00:23:59,135
Courtney's behavior appeared

618
00:23:59,136 --> 00:24:00,904
to relate to her HIP training.

619
00:24:00,905 --> 00:24:02,672
 Another HIP student
 was next.

620
00:24:02,673 --> 00:24:04,774
If a situation arose,

621
00:24:04,775 --> 00:24:07,210
I would definitely try
to be a hero if I could be.

622
00:24:07,211 --> 00:24:08,612
Or at least I would find
someone who could

623
00:24:08,613 --> 00:24:10,547
do something
better than me.

624
00:24:10,548 --> 00:24:12,749
 But would Elija
 live up to his prediction?

625
00:24:12,750 --> 00:24:14,784
No, turn around!
Turn around!

626
00:24:14,785 --> 00:24:16,553
I need water!

627
00:24:16,554 --> 00:24:18,755
What did I just say?
Turn around!

628
00:24:18,756 --> 00:24:23,693
How many times I have to
tell you something like that?

629
00:24:23,694 --> 00:24:25,262
But I was quiet.
I was--

630
00:24:25,263 --> 00:24:27,197
No, you weren't quiet,
and because of that,

631
00:24:27,198 --> 00:24:35,539
you're not going to have
any water, okay?

632
00:24:35,540 --> 00:24:36,973
-[man] All right.
-[Elijah] Let's go.

633
00:24:36,974 --> 00:24:38,909
-[Michael] Strength in numbers.
-[Elle] Oh, very good.

634
00:24:38,910 --> 00:24:41,177
He's our first person
to recruit confederates.

635
00:24:41,178 --> 00:24:44,114
He is. He's also
the leader of the group.

636
00:24:44,115 --> 00:24:44,815
Yes.

637
00:24:44,816 --> 00:24:46,049
 Utilizing the "be the first"

638
00:24:46,050 --> 00:24:47,751
 strategy from the class.

639
00:24:47,752 --> 00:24:49,152
You want some of my water?

640
00:24:49,153 --> 00:24:51,621
-That's fine.
-Thank you.

641
00:24:51,622 --> 00:24:54,925
 So far, two HIP students
 have displayed heroism.

642
00:24:54,926 --> 00:24:57,294
 Next, we tested a HIP student
 and a non-HIP student

643
00:24:57,295 --> 00:24:59,129
 at the same time.

644
00:24:59,130 --> 00:25:02,132
He's complaining
about water, as usual.

645
00:25:02,133 --> 00:25:05,969
-He's complaining about...
-I'm not complaining.

646
00:25:05,970 --> 00:25:08,972
After taking this class,
if I find myself in a situation

647
00:25:08,973 --> 00:25:11,174
where someone would need help,
I find myself more inclined

648
00:25:11,175 --> 00:25:13,777
to definitely step in
and step up.

649
00:25:13,778 --> 00:25:16,112
 Would Jessica step up?

650
00:25:16,113 --> 00:25:17,647
Stop complaining right now.

651
00:25:17,648 --> 00:25:20,317
I'm not.

652
00:25:20,318 --> 00:25:22,953
Really? Wow.

653
00:25:22,954 --> 00:25:26,590
I need some water.

654
00:25:26,591 --> 00:25:27,857
 Katherine and our actress

655
00:25:27,858 --> 00:25:29,893
 both got up to give
 the man water,

656
00:25:29,894 --> 00:25:37,167
 while the HIP student,
 Jessica, remained seated.

657
00:25:37,168 --> 00:25:39,135
 Katherine didn't take
 our HIP class.

658
00:25:39,136 --> 00:25:40,303
 Why did she intervene?

659
00:25:40,304 --> 00:25:43,306
 And why didn't the
 HIP student get up to help?

660
00:25:43,307 --> 00:25:45,642
Katherine, why do you
think you were first?

661
00:25:45,643 --> 00:25:47,944
I'm Greek and Italian,
so...

662
00:25:47,945 --> 00:25:49,012
You're not afraid
to step in?

663
00:25:49,013 --> 00:25:51,247
No, not at all.

664
00:25:51,248 --> 00:25:53,683
Jessica, you've been
through a program called HIP.

665
00:25:53,684 --> 00:25:55,085
Yes.

666
00:25:55,086 --> 00:25:56,953
Did you think
about that during this?

667
00:25:56,954 --> 00:25:58,622
Yes, a lot.
I wanted to stand up.

668
00:25:58,623 --> 00:26:00,924
I have really
pretty bad anxiety.

669
00:26:00,925 --> 00:26:03,793
I am not a very
confrontational person.

670
00:26:03,794 --> 00:26:05,629
Clearly the hero training class

671
00:26:05,630 --> 00:26:07,931
 was not the only factor
 at work here.

672
00:26:07,932 --> 00:26:09,866
 We ran the test
 several more times

673
00:26:09,867 --> 00:26:11,201
 with a mixed bag of results--

674
00:26:11,202 --> 00:26:14,904
 HIP students who helped...

675
00:26:14,905 --> 00:26:15,505
Yeah.

676
00:26:15,506 --> 00:26:16,272
She went looking for help.

677
00:26:16,273 --> 00:26:18,274
 HIP students
 who did nothing...

678
00:26:18,275 --> 00:26:21,845
 and non-HIP students
 who acted heroically.

679
00:26:21,846 --> 00:26:22,946
I'm going to just ask him
if he wants some water.

680
00:26:22,947 --> 00:26:24,881
[Elle]
She's doing it!

681
00:26:24,882 --> 00:26:27,083
-What's he doing here?
-He's moving. All right.

682
00:26:27,084 --> 00:26:29,285
Is he gonna secretly
give Barry water?

683
00:26:29,286 --> 00:26:30,920
Yes, thank you.

684
00:26:30,921 --> 00:26:33,123
 Our last subject
 of the day, Ruben,

685
00:26:33,124 --> 00:26:34,758
 did not take the HIP class,

686
00:26:34,759 --> 00:26:36,960
 and we decided to make
 taking heroic action

687
00:26:36,961 --> 00:26:38,828
 as difficult for him
 as possible.

688
00:26:38,829 --> 00:26:41,131
 We instructed
 our bystander actors

689
00:26:41,132 --> 00:26:43,299
 not to react
 to the elder abuse

690
00:26:43,300 --> 00:26:45,802
 or encourage Ruben
 in any way.

691
00:26:45,803 --> 00:26:47,737
[Barry] I didn't have
enough water.

692
00:26:47,738 --> 00:26:49,939
[Lisa]
We just got here, Barry.

693
00:26:49,940 --> 00:26:50,907
-I know, but I'm thirsty.
-Could you stop complaining?

694
00:26:50,908 --> 00:26:53,143
Just stop complaining.

695
00:26:53,144 --> 00:26:54,377
I just need some water,
that's all I need.

696
00:26:54,378 --> 00:26:56,112
Just a little bit of water.

697
00:26:56,113 --> 00:26:57,580
[Michael] He's got
this piercing look.

698
00:26:57,581 --> 00:27:01,184
He's clearly paying
attention, but there's
just no emotion there.

699
00:27:01,185 --> 00:27:04,187
 Yeah, and he's getting no
 feedback from the rest of the
 group.

700
00:27:04,188 --> 00:27:06,356
[Lisa] You're making a scene
for no reason.

701
00:27:06,357 --> 00:27:08,391
Hey, leave that alone.
Leave that alone.

702
00:27:08,392 --> 00:27:11,227
I just want some water.
I just want a little
bit of water.

703
00:27:11,228 --> 00:27:12,696
[Lisa]
Just-- Fine. Just relax.

704
00:27:12,697 --> 00:27:14,931
[Elle] Despite
the remarkable
social cost

705
00:27:14,932 --> 00:27:18,301
of getting up
in such a disaffected
group of people,

706
00:27:18,302 --> 00:27:19,803
he did it.

707
00:27:19,804 --> 00:27:20,671
If you don't want
to share the water,

708
00:27:20,672 --> 00:27:23,073
I can give him my water.
That's fine.

709
00:27:23,074 --> 00:27:25,975
-Is that okay?
-Wow.

710
00:27:25,976 --> 00:27:28,712
Personally, if you
were taking care of
my parent like that,

711
00:27:28,713 --> 00:27:32,015
there would be definitely some
lawsuits 'cause that's not the
way you treat somebody.

712
00:27:32,016 --> 00:27:34,918
 With no training
and no support from the group,

713
00:27:34,919 --> 00:27:36,853
 Ruben chose to be a hero.
 Why?

714
00:27:36,854 --> 00:27:39,489
If I don't take action,
then nobody else will.

715
00:27:39,490 --> 00:27:41,224
And I was like, I wish
I would have stood up sooner.

716
00:27:41,225 --> 00:27:43,059
Now I feel like, in the future,

717
00:27:43,060 --> 00:27:44,394
if I were to have
a situation like this,

718
00:27:44,395 --> 00:27:46,162
I wouldn't even think twice.

719
00:27:46,163 --> 00:27:48,498
 Scientists have
 studied heroism...

720
00:27:48,499 --> 00:27:50,133
...and one thing
they have found

721
00:27:50,134 --> 00:27:51,768
is that Hispanic and black males

722
00:27:51,769 --> 00:27:53,303
are the most likely
to intervene.

723
00:27:53,304 --> 00:27:55,371
Makes sense. Maybe
because of the background

724
00:27:55,372 --> 00:27:58,441
we come from-- as a minority,
we have to defend ourselves.

725
00:27:58,442 --> 00:28:01,010
And I think it's a subconscious
thing that we do.

726
00:28:01,011 --> 00:28:02,846
I'm just shocked right now.

727
00:28:02,847 --> 00:28:03,446
With flying colors,
might I add!

728
00:28:03,447 --> 00:28:06,483
Thank you.

729
00:28:06,484 --> 00:28:09,285
When it came to being a hero,
we found that the HIP class

730
00:28:09,286 --> 00:28:11,387
 could only help
 to a certain extent,

731
00:28:11,388 --> 00:28:14,457
 and individual background
 played a vital role.

732
00:28:14,458 --> 00:28:18,161
 So, can heroic behavior
 be taught,

733
00:28:18,162 --> 00:28:20,263
 or does it really
 boil down to personality?

734
00:28:20,264 --> 00:28:23,399
Ideally, an educational
program like ours

735
00:28:23,400 --> 00:28:26,469
should transcend
personality differences.

736
00:28:26,470 --> 00:28:28,938
But practice makes perfect.

737
00:28:28,939 --> 00:28:32,308
The key to heroism is
starting with very little steps,

738
00:28:32,309 --> 00:28:35,278
try to do a good deed
of kindness,

739
00:28:35,279 --> 00:28:37,180
and be willing to make
a bigger step.

740
00:28:37,181 --> 00:28:39,315
We had a very small sample
size in our demonstration,

741
00:28:39,316 --> 00:28:41,217
but we found that people
of color

742
00:28:41,218 --> 00:28:44,354
were much more likely
to take action. Why?

743
00:28:44,355 --> 00:28:46,089
If you're
a minority person,

744
00:28:46,090 --> 00:28:48,158
the system is
usually your enemy,

745
00:28:48,159 --> 00:28:50,527
so you can't say, Well,
the police will help,

746
00:28:50,528 --> 00:28:52,996
or the government will help
or the landlord will help,

747
00:28:52,997 --> 00:28:55,331
so it's me or no one.

748
00:28:55,332 --> 00:28:58,935
And so, you're just
more sensitive to
people in need.

749
00:28:58,936 --> 00:29:02,005
Mmm.

750
00:29:02,006 --> 00:29:03,907
Not all heroes are the same.

751
00:29:03,908 --> 00:29:05,542
The wisest course of action

752
00:29:05,543 --> 00:29:07,977
won't be the same
for any two people,

753
